dium wp-image-221" src="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/files/2010/10/C-moss-s-640x480.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" /></a>\n\n<a rel="attachment wp-att-222" href="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/?attachment_id=222"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-222" src="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/files/2010/10/HP-drawing-with-moss-s-360x480.jpg" alt="" width="360" height="480" /></a><a rel="attachment wp-att-224" href="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/?attachment_id=224"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-224" src="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/files/2010/10/spray-mist1-640x466.jpg" alt="" width="605" height="440" /></a>\n\n<a rel="attachment wp-att-225" href="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/?attachment_id=225"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-225" src="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/files/2010/10/C-painting-s-640x480.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" /></a>\n\nWe can build on all of this when we go out to the moors.\n\nPlastic sheet will be essential- not only to shelter under and listen to sounds  but to create a parade like atmosphere as we walk along with it trailing over our heads. We''ll take long paper as well, to raw on , wheel over, make sound with , wrap rocks in, do rubbings, drop and throw materials and objects onto.....', 'ravenscliffe 2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '217-autosave', '', '', '2010-10-20 09:45:54', '2010-10-20 09:45:54', '', 217, 'http://watershed.sallybarker.local/217-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(232, 2, '2010-11-03 15:31:13', '2010-11-03 15:31:13', 'I''m interested in the process that glaciers sculpted the land carving their way through valleys, leaving debris (the Hushings got its limestone from a glacier that meandered its way down from N. Yorkshire). I love the way they are so immense, so beautiful and so potentially devastating.\n\nI would like to explore possibilities with ice, and think that as winter sets in , the potential for working with freezing water will open up. For now though , I am looking at casting- creating casts of rock formations that I can take moulds from and use to cast in different materials- ice, jelly perhaps, plaster, resin- glass would be good.\n\nI have pressed small lumps of clay into the cracks and crevices that water erosion has created between rocks, the splits and fissures that mark all these beautiful rocks. They are waioting to be fiored - perhhapos then a mould can be taken for a liquid casting process- resin or ice. the final cast will be a shrunken versiom', 'starting a glacier', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '229-revision', '', '', '2010-11-03 15:31:13', '2010-11-03 15:31:13', '', 229, 'http://watershed.sallybarker.local/229-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(233, 2, '2010-11-03 21:46:58', '2010-11-03 21:46:58', 'I''m interested in the process that glaciers sculpted the land carving their way through valleys, leaving debris (the Hushings got its limestone from a glacier that meandered its way down from N. Yorkshire). I love the way they are so immense, so beautiful and so potentially devastating.\n\nsince the act of making something so latge can only be carried out by nature and since I want to approximate\n\nI would like to explore possibilities with ice, and think that as winter sets in , the potential for working with freezing water will open up. For now though , I am looking at casting- creating casts of rock formations that I can take moulds from and use to cast in different materials- ice, jelly perhaps, plaster, resin- glass would be good.\n\nI have pressed small lumps of clay into the cracks and crevices that water erosion has created between rocks, the splits and fissures that mark all these beautiful rocks. They are waioting to be fiored - perhhapos then a mould can be taken for a liquid casting process- resin or ice. the final cast will be a shrunken versiom of its former , real self , but that may be an interesteing debelopment?', 'starting a glacier', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '229-revision-2', '', '', '2010-11-03 21:46:58', '2010-11-03 21:46:58', '', 229, 'http://watershed.sallybarker.local/229-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
