(364, 3, '2011-03-20 15:32:43', '2011-03-20 15:32:43', '<a rel="attachment wp-att-366" href="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/trig-point-high-brown-knoll/3-trig-point-2/"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-366" src="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/files/2011/03/3-trig-point1-640x413.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="413" /></a>these trig points act as focal  punctuation marks - they dot the landscape: stark, white, concrete and minimal. Superceded now by GPS and aerial mapping but still used a lot by hikers. The metal bracket on the top would have held a theodolite. I love the way their obelisk shape looks so incongruous in the middle of nowhere. Hence the people, standing around, as if waiting for something of some significance to occur, unable/unwilling to avoid the circle.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'trig point- High Brown Knoll', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'trig-point-high-brown-knoll', '', '', '2012-09-21 09:04:33', '2012-09-21 09:04:33', '', 0, 'http://watershed.sallybarker.local/?p=364', 0, 'post', '', 1),
