(106, 3, '2012-01-12 00:16:38', '2012-01-11 23:16:38', '<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Case study</span></span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Experimental drawing in the forest- one day with group of 10 children </span></span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Here is an example of taking a group into the forest to draw with natural materials. Some of the children had never been into the forest before. </span></span>\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">They were encouraged to follow their instincts, forget about notions of "proper" drawing and explore the found &amp; supplied materials. The emphasis is on process and risk taking, not finished work. Results included 3D drawing in space as tape was wound around the tree; charcoal was cut with scissors to stick onto glue drawing; large sheets of paper "attacked" with ink and mud, Jackson Pollock style; twigs and leaves were sewn into a bed sheet; lines drawn into mud with twigs etc. </span></span>\n\n&nbsp;', 'Case Study: experimental drawing in the forest', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '79-revision', '', '', '2012-01-12 00:16:38', '2012-01-11 23:16:38', '', 79, 'http://sallybarker.local/uncategorized/79-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(108, 3, '2012-01-12 00:09:05', '2012-01-11 23:09:05', '<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">Case Study- ice</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">ice workshop- creatively developing curriculum topic "materials"- year 5, half day</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">This is one of many workshops I''ve run with ice- it holds surprise., intrigue, lots of science, maths &amp; literacy potential and is fun.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">materials- lots of dfferent sized containers (inc carrier bags full!), of ice embedded with objects, text, food colouring, foodstuffs, flowers etc. Give children plastic cup to take home &amp; freeze, the day before. Plastic trays, tools to explore (eg satay sticks, toffee hammers, forks), paper, plastic, rulers, salt, food colour/paint, brushes, lots of paper towels</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">working with ice . </span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">The children took home a plastic cup and froze an object in water. The workshop was open and exploratory, - they experimented in small groups at their tables, chipping out the objects, scratching, building constructions using paper etc. Questions embedded in ice - relating to ice around the world (geography). Investigate how different materials stick to the ice, they played ice games ,building tallest tower etc. Then, together, we built a large, floor based sculptural installation with different ice blocks, explored the effects of salt, painted with food colouring, chipped at it etc. </span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">Critical discussion in a group circle at the beginning and end.</span>\n\n&nbsp;', 'Caes Study-ICE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '92-revision', '', '', '2012-01-12 00:09:05', '2012-01-11 23:09:05', '', 92, 'http://sallybarker.local/uncategorized/92-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(107, 3, '2012-01-12 00:16:40', '2012-01-11 23:16:40', '<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Case study</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Experimental drawing in the forest- one day with group of 10 children </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Here is an example of taking a group into the forest to draw with natural materials. Some of the children had never been into the forest before. </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">They were encouraged to follow their instincts, forget about notions of "proper" drawing and explore the found &amp; supplied materials. The emphasis is on process and risk taking, not finished work. Results included 3D drawing in space as tape was wound around the tree; charcoal was cut with scissors to stick onto glue drawing; large sheets of paper "attacked" with ink and mud, Jackson Pollock style; twigs and leaves were sewn into a bed sheet; lines drawn into mud with twigs etc. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Case Study: experimental drawing in the forest', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '79-revision-2', '', '', '2012-01-12 00:16:40', '2012-01-11 23:16:40', '', 79, 'http://sallybarker.local/uncategorized/79-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(109, 3, '2012-09-21 12:44:57', '2012-09-21 11:44:57', 'Some images from several art club sessions with a group of referred children, run with an art therapist.\r\n\r\nThis was very powerful work around issues of identity,  self esteem, communication, control. They projected images, textures, objects and text onto each other, altered their appearance and performed.', 'Performative projection work', 'This was very powerful work around issues of identity,  self esteem, communication, control. They projected images, textures, objects and text onto each other, altered their appearance and performed.', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'performative-projection-work', '', '', '2012-12-01 22:56:57', '2012-12-01 21:56:57', '', 0, 'http://sallybarker.local/?page_id=109', 7, 'education', '', 0),
(639, 1, '2012-12-01 22:51:18', '2012-12-01 21:51:18', 'The drawing shed was an Arts Council funded project in collaboration with artist Sally Labern, running BIG drawing days in an area of Walthamstow, East London, Part of the Be Creative Be Well initiative.\n\nIn 2009 artist Sally Labern and I were commissioned by Arts Council England, to develop a project we called “the drawing shed”, as part of their Be Creative Be Well strand. Together with architect Mark Parsons from <a href="http://www.studiopolpo.com/">studio polpo</a>, we designed and constructed a mobile drawing studio, which we wheeled around the streets of Walthamstow, inviting people to join us in drawing guerilla style, en route to venues. On arrival, the shed folds out, ramps down and is used as a base for drawing, in all its forms. We papered out whole rooms, leading group and individual drawing sessions, some started with a yoga trainer, stretching and drawing with the whole body, using graphite sticks to make marks.\n\nBased at the local YMCA, we worked with many different groups using drawing as a form of communication and social cohesion - we had amazing outcomes. An outdoor drawing day on the estate brought residents together with ymca residents over tea and drawing. We papered an adventure play area for some physical action with a group of young adults with learning and physical disabilities. A whole year 6 group drew together. We took the drawing shed to the Green Fair and led a mass drawing event in the park, using paper from all the projects, the paper almost taking off with a gust of wind, and then turned into a bed! Finally we ran a hugely successful drawing day (for The Big Draw) at an abandoned Woolies building in Leytonstone, with 400 people dropping in and 100 square meters of paper. The drawing shed has been given further funding by The Arts Council.\n\nThe Campaign for Drawing features it as a case study:\n\n<a href="http://www.campaignfordrawing.net/the-big-draw/critical-mass-draw">http://www.campaignfordrawing.net/the-big-draw/critical-mass-draw</a>\n\nThe project was also highly commended by the Barbara Whatmore Charitable Trust\n\nThere is a video of the shed and interviews for the Well London website here:\n\n<a href="http://www.london.gov.uk/welllondon/casestudies/drawingShed.jsp">http://www.london.gov.uk/welllondon/casestudies/drawingShed.jsp</a>\n\n<a href="http://www.studiopolpo.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=97%3Adrawingshed&amp;Itemid=58">Artice on www.studiopolpo.com</a>\n\nSince I disappeared and moved up North, I''m happy to report the drawing shed continues and grows without me! Sally Labern now collaborates with Bobby Lloyd on 2 new projects Print Bike and ClayOven.\n\nGo to : <a href="http://www.thedrawingshed.org">http://www.thedrawingshed.org</a>\n\nI continue to independently run <a title="Case study – Group drawing days" href="http://sallybarker.local/education/group-drawing-days/">body drawing days</a>.', 'the drawing shed', 'The drawing shed was an Arts Council funded project in collaboration with artist Sally Labern, running BIG drawing days in an area of Walthamstow, East London, Part of the Be Creative Be Well initiative. The project was highly commended by the Barbara Whatmore Charitable Trust, and the Campaign for Drawing features it as a case study.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '245-autosave', '', '', '2012-12-01 22:51:18', '2012-12-01 21:51:18', '', 245, 'http://sallybarker.local/blog/2012/12/01/245-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(630, 1, '2012-12-01 13:26:17', '2012-12-01 12:26:17', '<ul>\n	<li>one day workshop</li>\n	<li>8 - 12 adults, dependent on venue size</li>\n</ul>\nThis day long workshop was held with 8 adults, with no specific physical requirements . Body drawing workshops are tailored to fit the needs &amp; number of participants and the size and physical detail of the venue. Any age, ability and level of fitness. Experimental, fun and thought provoking in a physical way.\n\nThe floor and up the walls are papered, potentially furniture too. The group physically explore the 3D space and are led through relaxation and breathing excercises, body awareness, trust building, exploratory individual mark making,intimate and private drawing, choreographed group work, finally turning the whole 2D drawing into a sculptural installation, getting inside and drawing with torches. The paper can be torn up to take home!\n\nThe emphasis is on experimental, thoughtful mark making and drawing with lots of opportunity to share thoughts, self and peer critique / direction and laughing!\n\nClothing suitable for getting messy and dirty essential.\n\nFor images of different drawing groups please go to <a title="the drawing shed" href="http://sallybarker.local/education/the-drawing-shed/">the drawing shed</a>.', 'Case study - Group drawing days', 'This day long workshop was held with 8 adults, with no specific physical requirements . Body drawing workshops are tailored to fit the needs & number of participants and the size and physical detail of the venue. Any age, ability and level of fitness. Experimental, fun and thought provoking in a physical way.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '267-autosave', '', '', '2012-12-01 13:26:17', '2012-12-01 12:26:17', '', 267, 'http://sallybarker.local/blog/2012/12/01/267-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
