(142, 3, '2012-01-12 00:18:03', '2012-01-11 23:18:03', '<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">Case Study- ice</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">ice workshop- creatively developing curriculum topic "materials"- year 5, half day</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">This is one of many workshops I''ve run with ice- it holds surprise., intrigue, lots of science, maths &amp; literacy potential and is fun.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">materials- lots of dfferent sized containers (inc carrier bags full!), of ice embedded with objects, text, food colouring, foodstuffs, flowers etc. Give children plastic cup to take home &amp; freeze, the day before. Plastic trays, tools to explore (eg satay sticks, toffee hammers, forks), paper, plastic, rulers, salt, food colour/paint, brushes, lots of paper towels</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">working with ice . </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">The children took home a plastic cup and froze an object in water. The workshop was open and exploratory, - they experimented in small groups at their tables, chipping out the objects, scratching, building constructions using paper etc. Questions embedded in ice - relating to ice around the world (geography). Investigate how different materials stick to the ice, they played ice games ,building tallest tower etc. Then, together, we built a large, floor based sculptural installation with different ice blocks, explored the effects of salt, painted with food colouring, chipped at it etc. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">Critical discussion in a group circle at the beginning and end.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Caes Study-ICE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '92-revision-2', '', '', '2012-01-12 00:18:03', '2012-01-11 23:18:03', '', 92, 'http://sallybarker.local/uncategorized/92-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(143, 3, '2012-01-12 01:08:41', '2012-01-12 00:08:41', '<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">I like to use strange and forgotten or overlooked spaces that, when given some attention and nurturing with the childrens work, results in something very positive, powerful and meaningful. They can represent the un-beautiful, the imperfect but interesting and characterful. When we give attention to something previuosly missed we celebrate the act of looking closer at our environment. These displays in neglected spaces invests in ourselves,and  create a form of community.</span></span>', 'display in neglected spaces', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '114-revision', '', '', '2012-01-12 01:08:41', '2012-01-12 00:08:41', '', 114, 'http://sallybarker.local/uncategorized/114-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(144, 3, '2012-01-12 00:51:39', '2012-01-11 23:51:39', 'these are some images of a couple of dens groups have made with me. They combine a place to hide, tell stories, show work, develop construction skills, collaborate,explore materials, use proper tools,enjoy being outdoors (though we''ve made indoor ones too). Anything goes.', 'creative den making', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '126-revision', '', '', '2012-01-12 00:51:39', '2012-01-11 23:51:39', '', 126, 'http://sallybarker.local/uncategorized/126-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(145, 3, '2012-01-12 01:08:26', '2012-01-12 00:08:26', '<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">Case Study- ice</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">ice workshop- creatively developing curriculum topic "materials"- year 5, half day</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">This is one of many workshops I''ve run with ice- it holds surprise., intrigue, lots of science, maths &amp; literacy potential and is fun.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">materials- lots of dfferent sized containers (inc carrier bags full!), of ice embedded with objects, text, food colouring, foodstuffs, flowers etc. Give children plastic cup to take home &amp; freeze, the day before. Plastic trays, tools to explore (eg satay sticks, toffee hammers, forks), paper, plastic, rulers, salt, food colour/paint, brushes, lots of paper towels</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">working with ice . </span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">The children took home a plastic cup and froze an object in water. The workshop was open and exploratory, - they experimented in small groups at their tables, chipping out the objects, scratching, building constructions using paper etc. Questions embedded in ice - relating to ice around the world (geography). Investigate how different materials stick to the ice, they played ice games ,building tallest tower etc. Then, together, we built a large, floor based sculptural installation with different ice blocks, explored the effects of salt, painted with food colouring, chipped at it etc. </span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">Critical discussion in a group circle at the beginning and end.</span>\n\n&nbsp;', 'Caes Study-ICE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '92-revision-3', '', '', '2012-01-12 01:08:26', '2012-01-12 00:08:26', '', 92, 'http://sallybarker.local/uncategorized/92-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(146, 3, '2012-01-12 00:17:52', '2012-01-11 23:17:52', '<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Case study</span></span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Experimental drawing in the forest- one day with group of 10 children </span></span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Here is an example of taking a group into the forest to draw with natural materials. Some of the children had never been into the forest before. </span></span>\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">They were encouraged to follow their instincts, forget about notions of "proper" drawing and explore the found &amp; supplied materials. The emphasis is on process and risk taking, not finished work. Results included 3D drawing in space as tape was wound around the tree; charcoal was cut with scissors to stick onto glue drawing; large sheets of paper "attacked" with ink and mud, Jackson Pollock style; twigs and leaves were sewn into a bed sheet; lines drawn into mud with twigs etc. </span></span>\n\n&nbsp;', 'Case Study: experimental drawing in the forest', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '79-revision-3', '', '', '2012-01-12 00:17:52', '2012-01-11 23:17:52', '', 79, 'http://sallybarker.local/uncategorized/79-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
