(227, 3, '2012-01-18 15:48:48', '2012-01-18 14:48:48', '<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This is work that has come out of The Watershed Project and is the start of exploratory work- initially on a small scale but in anticipation of larger more complex work.The pieces play with contrasting texture, colour, and weight,and technique, often referencing the land. The wool is very local and I''m hand spinning it using black, "Shetland" wool and cream, "Wensleydale" wool; the stone and slate, is rescued from the farm where I grew up. I am exploiting the potential of the materials, giving them new roles, subverting their character and playing with different combinations to offer a fresh perspective. Small stones often represent bigger, landscape sized rocks and act like maquettes.</span></span>\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commissions start at £40 for the slate drawings,</span></span>\n\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">£70 for the mini-scaffolding bell jars , £80 if figures are customised as portraits (choose figure &amp; clothing)\n</span></span>', 'recent , exploratory work with locally sourced materials', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '212-revision', '', '', '2012-01-18 15:48:48', '2012-01-18 14:48:48', '', 212, 'http://sallybarker.local/uncategorized/212-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(229, 3, '2012-01-17 16:41:43', '2012-01-17 15:41:43', '<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">Creative Partnerships project at The Avenue Special Needs School in Reading , 2009 The Enquiry question was<span style="font-size: small;">:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #003399;"> <span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><em>In what ways can the practice of increasing sensory awareness of particular spaces and </em><em>natural materials be developed by staff and pupils to increase the effectiveness of the teaching/learning curriculum?</em></span></span></span>\r\n\r\nI worked with 2 classes: ASD and a PMLD /MLD mixed group\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">We explored the physical space through large scale physical drawing with the whole body, exploring ice and many other materials. We made cardboard and paper dens, structures for developing communication,, sensory and motor skills, and construction skills.. </span></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">We created a legacy for the work rather than deliver a finite result- so the staff and students would continue to develop new ideas and outcomes. We made a drawing structure – a frame that could easily be brought out and "planted" in the ground for the attachment of different drawing surfaces, instruments , sensory materials . I made an interactive screen/ den for the playground which had lots of possibilities for continuing use and development as an outdoor educational resource and play structure and den.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif;">Ideas from this project went on to inform my next creative partnerships project at St Benedicts<span style="color: #0000ff;"><em>.</em></span></span>', 'SEN  case study', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '177-revision-5', '', '', '2012-01-17 16:41:43', '2012-01-17 15:41:43', '', 177, 'http://sallybarker.local/uncategorized/177-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
