(581, 3, '2012-09-24 23:33:46', '2012-09-24 22:33:46', 'For "This is not an Empty Space",we (myself with  a group of local artists) took over a floor of a n abandoned mill in Hebden.  The interior wall of the mill, which backed on to the hillside, had hundreds of mysterious holes, full of soil , some running with water- the whole wall was damp and alive, the space smelt strongly of mould.   I dug up and planted 50 living local saplings into these existing holes. I  made two  seductive, gold fountains (using the same gold metal sheet that I had used on "Misfit" in 2008)  and placed one next to the wall which was running with water and the other in a swampy hole in the flagged floor.The fountains had a very temporary, glamorous look to them. The saplings looked perky and fresh. The wall was  both glistenening and slick with patches of mould and moss growth - and slimy and disintegrating with the decay of neglect.\r\n\r\nThrough the combination of incongruous, dry fountains and "suitable",  living saplings, this piece continues to expolore  themes of belonging, identity and sustainability.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'This is not an Empty Space', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'this-is-not-an-empty-space', '', '', '2012-12-01 23:28:44', '2012-12-01 22:28:44', '', 0, 'http://sallybarker.local/?post_type=art&#038;p=581', 6, 'art', '', 0),
