(624, 1, '2012-10-16 23:55:56', '2012-10-16 22:55:56', 'For "This is not an Empty Space",we (myself with  a group of local artists) took over a floor of a n abandoned mill in Hebden.  The interior wall of the mill, which backed on to the hillside, had hundreds of mysterious holes, full of soil , some running with water- the whole wall was damp and alive, the space smelt strongly of mould.   I dug up and planted 50 living local saplings into these existing holes. I  made two  seductive, gold fountains (using the same gold metal sheet that I had used on "Misfit" in 2008)  and placed one next to the wall which was running with water and the other in a swampy hole in the flagged floor.The fountains had a very temporary, glamorous look to them. The saplings looked perky and fresh. The wall was  both glistenening and slick with patches of mould and moss growth - and slimy and disintegrating with the decay of neglect.\n\nThrough the combination of incongruous, dry fountains and "suitable",  living saplings, this piece continues to expolore  themes of belonging, identity and sustainability.\n\n&nbsp;', 'This is not an Empty Space', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '581-autosave', '', '', '2012-10-16 23:55:56', '2012-10-16 22:55:56', '', 581, 'http://sallybarker.local/blog/2012/10/16/581-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
